sketchBlocks.bodyMarkdown:
A base-class contract works best when each subclass keeps the same method name but returns its own version of the result. That is how abstraction supports polymorphism.

Here is a small example with two subclasses:

```python
class BaseItem:
    def __init__(self, title):
        self.title = title

    def storage_label(self):
        return self.title


class Book(BaseItem):
    def storage_label(self):
        return f"BOOK::{self.title}"


class Video(BaseItem):
    def storage_label(self):
        return f"VIDEO::{self.title}"
```

Line by line:

- `BaseItem` says every item should have a `storage_label()` method.
- `Book` and `Video` both keep that exact method name.
- Each subclass returns a different format.

Because the method name stays the same, a service can call `storage_label()` on either object without needing separate branches first. That shared method name is the contract.

